{{infobox planet | minorplanet = yes | name = C/2016 R2 | image = C 2016 R2 PanSTARRS.jpg | caption = The comet on 16 January 2018 | background = #FFE0C2 | discovery_ref = &thinsp;<ref name="MPEC2016-R107">{{cite web |title=MPEC 2016-R107: COMET C/2016 R2 (PANSTARRS) |publisher=[[IAU Minor Planet Center]] |date=2016-09-09 |url=https://www.minorplanetcenter.org/mpec/K16/K16RA7.html |accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref> | discoverer = [[Pan-STARRS]] | discovery_site = [[Haleakala Observatory|Haleakala Obs.]] | discovered = 30 August 2016 | mpc_name = C/2016 R2 | mp_category = [[comet]]&thinsp; | orbit_ref = &thinsp;<ref name="jpldata">{{cite web |type = 2018-04-13 last obs. |title = JPL Small-Body Database Browser: C/2016 R2 (PANSTARRS) |url = https://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=2016R2 |publisher = [[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]] |accessdate = 26 November 2018}}</ref> | epoch = 13 October 2018 | observation_arc = 774 days | eccentricity = 0.99646 | perihelion = 2.60235 [[Astronomical unit|AU]] | inclination = 58.222° | moid = 1.72 AU | asc_node = 80.5685° | mean_anomaly = 359.9932° | arg_peri = 33.1930° | abs_magnitude = 8<ref name="jpldata"/> }} '''C/2016 R2 (PANSTARRS)''' is a [[comet]], discovered using the [[Pan-STARRS]] telescopes on September 7, 2016. The comet has recently attracted attention from many astronomers as it approaches its closest point to the sun in May 2018.<ref>https://apod.nasa.gov/apod/ap180112.html</ref> It has been observed to have a very complex [[Comet tail|tail]], which has been suggested to be due to a fast rotation period of the nucleus.
The comet orbits the Sun on a 20,000 year orbit, which takes it out about 740 AU (Sun-Earth distances).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://phys.org/news/2018-05-comet-c2016-r2-pan-starrs-rich.html|title=Comet C/2016 R2 (Pan-STARRS) is rich in carbon monoxide and depleted in hydrogen cyanide, study finds|access-date=2018-11-17}}</ref> It was found to differ from typical comets, and was found to be rich in [[Carbon monoxide|carbon monixide]] (CO) with a blue [[Coma (cometary)|coma]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://phys.org/news/2018-05-comet-c2016-r2-pan-starrs-rich.html|title=Comet C/2016 R2 (Pan-STARRS) is rich in carbon monoxide and depleted in hydrogen cyanide, study finds|access-date=2018-11-17}}</ref> The blue color is though to come from the rich amounts of carbon monoxide being [[ionized]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.space.com/39579-rare-blue-carbon-monoxide-comet-photos.html|title=Rare Carbon-Monoxide Comet Turns Blue in Stunning Deep-Space Photos|work=Space.com|access-date=2018-11-17}}</ref> The comet was also noted to be rich in [[nitrogen]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sci-news.com/astronomy/blue-comet-c2016-r2-06506.html|title=Astronomers Spot Rare Blue Comet: C/2016 R2 {{!}} Astronomy {{!}} Sci-News.com|work=Breaking Science News {{!}} Sci-News.com|access-date=2018-11-17|language=en-US}}</ref>
The comet was observed by a submillimeter wavelength telescope in the late 2010s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://phys.org/news/2018-05-comet-c2016-r2-pan-starrs-rich.html|title=Comet C/2016 R2 (Pan-STARRS) is rich in carbon monoxide and depleted in hydrogen cyanide, study finds|access-date=2018-11-17}}</ref>
The comet made its closest approach to the Sun in May 2018, and its blue, teal, and dust tail were noted as an astronomical target.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.space.com/39579-rare-blue-carbon-monoxide-comet-photos.html|title=Rare Carbon-Monoxide Comet Turns Blue in Stunning Deep-Space Photos|work=Space.com|access-date=2018-11-17}}</ref> Blue comets are a less common type of comet.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sci-news.com/astronomy/blue-comet-c2016-r2-06506.html|title=Astronomers Spot Rare Blue Comet: C/2016 R2 {{!}} Astronomy {{!}} Sci-News.com|work=Breaking Science News {{!}} Sci-News.com|access-date=2018-11-17|language=en-US}}</ref>
