In the [[Kalevala]] rune entitled "Haava" (The Wound, section 8),<ref>Bosley, K., translator (1999) ''The Kalevala.'' Oxford World's Classics. Oxford: Oxford University Press.</ref> [[Väinämöinen]] attempts a heroic feat that results in a gushing wound, the blood from which covers the entire earth. This deluge is not emphasized in the Kalevala version redacted by [[Elias Lönnrot]], but the global quality of the flood is evident in original variants of the rune. In one variant collected in [[Northern Ostrobothnia]] in 1803/04, the rune tells:

: ''The blood came forth like a flood<br />''
: ''the gore ran like a river:<br />''
: ''there was no hummock<br />''
: ''and no high mountain<br />''
: ''that was not flooded<br />''
: ''all from Väinämöinen's toe
: ''from the holy hero's knee.''<ref>Kuusi, M., Bosley, K., and Branch, M., editors and translators (1977) ''Finnish folk poetry: epic: an anthology in Finnish and English.'' Helsinki: [[Finnish Literature Society]]. p 94</ref>

[[Matti Kuusi]] notes in his analysis that the rune's motifs of constructing a boat, a wound, and a flood have parallels with flood myths from around the world.<ref>Kuusi, M., Bosley, K., and Branch, M., editors and translators (1977) ''Finnish folk poetry: epic: an anthology in Finnish and English.'' Helsinki: [[Finnish Literature Society]].</ref> There are sources that cite this flood mythology to the nature of Kalevala as a [[comparative mythology]], which borrowed elements from stories found in other ancient sources such as the [[Persian people|Persians]], [[Phoenicians]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Eclectic Magazine of Foreign Literature, Science, and Art, Volume 42|last=Bidwell|first=W.H.|publisher=Leavitt, Trow, & Company|year=1857|isbn=|location=New York|pages=364}}</ref> the Bible and the Greek mythology, then integrated it with the myth's personification of nature.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=nUYUAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA154&dq=flood+myth+kalevala&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiX1ebmg-HcAhXIxLwKHY-SAJAQ6AEIQjAF#v=onepage&q=flood%20myth%20kalevala&f=false|title=The Presbyterian Quarterly|last=Stickler|first=G.B|last2=Barnett|first2=E.H.|date=1889|publisher=Constitution Publishing Company|year=1889|isbn=|location=New York|pages=154|language=en}}</ref> The account of the great flood was embedded in a narrative that also featured the Greek [[Solar deity|sun-myths]] and [[List of lunar deities|moon-myths]]. These influences are not found in the myths of Finland's [[Slavs|Slavic]] and [[Scandinavia|Scandinavian]] neighbors. However, a theory explained this aspect to Finnish myth as a relic of the earliest Asiatic life of one of the Finnish ancestors, the [[Finno-Ugric peoples|Ugrian tribes]].

According to [[Anna-Leena Siikala]], Väinämöinen's legs are of mythological and [[creation myth|cosmogonic]] significance throughout Finnish mythology. For example, it is originally on Väinämöinen's knee that the primordial water-fowl first lays the [[world egg]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Siikala|first=Anna-Leena|title=Itämerensuomalainen mytologia|year=2012|publisher=[[Finnish Literature Society]]|location=Helsinki|isbn=978-952-222-393-7|pages=536|url=https://kirjat.finlit.fi/index.php?showitem=2596}}</ref>

